<HEADLINE>
FT  02 JUL 93 / World Stock Markets (America): Dow retreats after drop in
NAPM index
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PATRICK HARVERSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Wall Street
AFTER a brief move upwards at the opening, US share prices fell back in the
wake of more bad economic news to end little changed on the day, writes
Patrick Harverson in New York.
At the close, the Dow Jones Industrial Average was down 5.54 at 3,510.54.
The more broadly based Standard&amp;Poor's 500 finished 1.53 lower at 449.00,
while the Amex composite ended up 1.63 at 435.87, and the Nasdaq composite
down 0.36 at 703.59. Trading volume on the NYSE was 283m shares.
Prices opened slightly firmer, helped by reports of an 11,000 decline in the
latest weekly jobless claims numbers. The fall was bigger than expected and
briefly raised hopes that today's employment report for June will not be as
weak as feared.
The markets could not hold on to their initial gains, however, and prices
turned tail soon after the National Association of Purchasing Management
reported that its index of manufacturing activity had dropped from 51.1 per
cent in May to 49.8 per cent in June. Any reading below 50 per cent is
regarded as indicative of a contraction in the manufacturing economy.
Moreover, the June figure was the lowest level in the NAPM index since
December 1991, a time when the economy was in recession.
The data was especially worrying because it suggested that it was unlikely
that manufacturers added to their payrolls in any significant numbers last
month. Consequently, today's June employment report could prove even weaker
than anticipated. The latest batch of Wall Street forecasts predict that
non-farm payrolls will have risen by between 100,000 and 150,000 last month,
and that the unemployment rate will be at 7.0 per cent.
Cyclicals ended mixed despite the fresh economic worries. General Electric
dropped Dollars  5/8 to Dollars 95, Caterpillar gave up Dollars  7/8 at
Dollars 74, but Minnesota Mining&amp;Manufacturing held steady at Dollars 108,
and International Paper bounced back from early losses to finish Dollars 1
3/8 higher at Dollars 65 3/8 ,.
Aluminium Company of America rallied strongly, rising Dollars 2 1/8 to
Dollars 72 1/8 as the stock continued to benefit from its recent decision to
cut its aluminium production capacity.
Westinghouse Electric firmed Dollars  1/8 to Dollars 16 as investors
responded mostly favourably to the appointment of Mr Michael Jordan as
chairman and chief executive.
Santa Fe Pacific slipped Dollars  1/4 to Dollars 18 after Merrill Lynch cut
its short-term rating on the stock from above average to neutral.
Drug stocks ran into heavy selling after two of the sector's biggest
constituents - Merck and Pfizer - were cut from the recommended list of
Goldman Sachs. Pfizer tumbled Dollars 2 1/8 to Dollars 64 7/8 in volume of
2.1m shares, Merck gave up Dollars  5/8 at Dollars 34 7/8 , Bristol-Myers
Squibb dropped Dollars  7/8 to Dollars 57 and Schering-Plough fell Dollars 1
3/8 to Dollars 68 1/2 .
Toronto was closed yesterday for Canada Day.
