<PROFILE>_AN-DGBCVAGMFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>930702
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  02 JUL 93 / International Company News: IBM wins rulings against
Comdisco
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LOUISE KEHOE
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   SAN FRANCISCO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
INTERNATIONAL Business Machines has won two rulings in its lawsuit against
Comdisco, the leading computer leasing company. A Delaware court has ruled
that Comdisco misappropriated IBM property by removing and then selling or
leasing parts of a computer owned by IBM Credit.
The court granted summary judgment to IBM, and ruled that other charges
brought against Comdisco should go to a jury for final determination.
The IBM lawsuit, filed in 1991, charged that Comdisco engaged in 'elaborate
schemes in which property belonging to IBM Credit Corporation was illegally
transferred, released, or sold'. The suit was part of a broader dispute
between IBM and the computer leasing industry over business practices.
Comdisco and other computer leasing companies complained that IBM was
attempting to thwart competition in the market. Parts of mainframe computers
are typically swapped during the upgrading the equipment. IBM claimed,
however, that this practice prevented it from keeping track of its property
and violated its leasing agreements.
'From the outset, our position was that you cannot take and dispose of
property that belongs to someone else, said Mr Harry Kavetas, IBM
vice-president and president of IBM Credit Corporation.
Comdisco, however, said it was pleased the court remanded to trial other
aspects of the dispute. 'We look forward to the opportunity to present our
case on the issues involving sub-leasing and over-leasing, said Mr Kenneth
Pontikes, chairman and president.
'Comdisco's ultimate vindication in this case will also be a victory for the
computer leasing industry generally, which has been operating under a great
cloud of uncertainty since IBM first filed this litigation two years ago.'
</TEXT>
<XX>
