FT  02 JUL 93 / International Company News: McDonnell Douglas puts
helicopter plans on hold
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MARTIN DICKSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
McDONNELL Douglas, the US defence and aerospace group, said yesterday that
it had decided not to actively pursue the sale of its helicopter business or
its involvement in a joint venture.
The company, which announced last year that it was exploring partnership and
sale possibilities, said it had intensively evaluated a number of serious
prospects but had concluded that a partnership or sale at this time was not
in the best interests of the company or its customers.
The helicopter unit, which is based at Mesa, Arizona, produces the AH-64
Apache attack helicopter and the MD 500 and MD Explorer commercial lines.
McDonnell Douglas said it would now fully integrate the unit into its
McDonnell Douglas aerospace business.
McDonnell Douglas also announced yesterday that its second-quarter results
would include Dollars 57m of unusual after-tax gains. Some Dollars 43m would
come from the partial reversal of a charge taken in the first quarter of
last year for the adoption of a new accounting standard on retirees' health
benefits.
</TEXT>
