<HEADLINE>
FT  02 JUL 93 / International Company News: IBM plans to market its Ambra
range in the US
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LOUISE KEHOE
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   SAN FRANCISCO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
IBM, the US computer maker, plans to form a subsidiary to sell low-cost
personal computers in the US under the Ambra brand name, mirroring its
earlier moves in Europe and Canada.
It has also formed a new division within its personal systems organisation
to develop a new generation of high-performance desktop and PCs based on the
Power PC microprocessor it has developed with Apple Computer and Motorola of
the US.
The moves reflect IBM's determination to extend its lead in the PC market by
offering products that appeal to all segments.
While the formation of the US Ambra subsidiary may give IBM a boost in PC
profits in the near term, the new division represents a long-term strategic
effort to ensure IBM is strongly positioned in an emerging segment of the PC
market.
Ambra will offer products aimed at price sensitive buyers and will compete
directly with the 'clones' of IBM's PCs offered by lesser-known
manufacturers. As in the UK, where Ambra was introduced last year, the
product line will not carry IBM's name and the subsidiary company will
operate independently.
Ambra US could represent a serious threat to second and third-tier PC
manufacturers in the US who are already feeling the pressure of intense
price competition.
In contrast, the newly-formed Power Personal Systems division is an in-house
effort to benefit from IBM's substantial investments in Power PC
microprocessors for PC products.
By placing the development group in a separate division, IBM aims to
maintain the focus of its existing PC business on development of PCs using
Intel microprocessors.
IBM's semiconductor partner in the Power PC chip effort is touting the new
chips as having 'the power to blow away Pentium,' Intel's latest
microprocessor chip.
IBM PC, however, has no plans to abandon the Intel architecture and is
developing PC products using 'Pentium and future Intel microprocessors,' a
spokesman said.
However, IBM aims to make the most of its investment in Power PC by offering
the broadest possible range of products using the new technology.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Companies:-
</XX>
<CO>International Business Machines Corp.
</CO>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>USZ   United States of America.
</CN>
