<HEADLINE>
FT  02 JUL 93 / UK Company News: Pace hots up for new equity issues
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW BOLGER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THERE HAS been a surge of new equity issues on the London Stock Exchange
with the amount raised in the first half of this year already exceeding the
total for the whole of last year by 6.6 per cent.
According to a survey by IFR Securities Data, a total of Pounds 11.8bn has
so far been raised this year, compared with Pounds 11bn in the previous 12
months. This year's first half total of 294 new issues is 72 per cent ahead
of the same stage last year.
IFR said this represented a remarkable turnaround in both the willingness of
companies to seek new capital, and in investor confidence.
Rights issues continued to be the preferred method of capital raising, with
Pounds 7.48bn of the Pounds 11.8bn raised this year having been through cash
calls. Last year they accounted for 34 per cent of the volume underwritten,
but the figure now stands at 64 per cent.
The Zeneca cash call represented 18 per cent of this total, and 11.5 per
cent of the whole domestic new equity issues market. The property sector
accounted for 12.8 per cent of rights activity, with large issues from
Slough Estates, Hammerson, British Land and MEPC.
SG Warburg leads the league table of merchant bankers handling the new
equity issues, having raised Pounds 1.96bn so far this year - 16.6 per cent
of the total - from 39 issues. IFR said that Warburg's dominance of the
market this year already seemed assured.
Lazard Brothers is second, with Pounds 1.18bn underwritten in the first half
from 11 issues. BZW is third, with a total of Pounds 1.15bn from 20 issues.
Morgan Grenfell is fourth, having raised Pounds 1.12bn from eight issues.
With established UK houses at the top, the survey said Goldman Sachs and
Morgan Stanley were leading a cautious American move into the market.
</TEXT>
