<HEADLINE>
FT  02 JUL 93 / Fund managers move to in-house research
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD GOURLAY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
INSTITUTIONAL fund managers are increasingly bypassing stockbrokers and
making direct contact with companies' senior management, according to the
Extel Survey of Investment Analysts.
More than one-third of the fund managers questioned said they were paying
more visits to companies, with most of the trips initiated by themselves
rather than the company or the broker.
The trend towards more direct contact with companies will add to the
competitive pressure on smaller stockbroking houses, already been hit by
institutions reducing the number of brokers they use.
Mr Geoffrey Osmint, consulting editor of the Extel survey, said fund
managers were doing more in-house research on their own ideas, and spending
less time talking to brokers. 'It used to be the case that no-one would
invest a penny in smaller companies without seeing the colour of the
management's eyes.' Increasing numbers of institutions were now applying the
same rigour to investing in larger companies.
Some of the 122 fund managers who responded had made several hundred company
visits. One institution recorded 600 visits. Overall, two-thirds of all
company visits were initiated by the managers or the company and not the
broker.
The fund managers said the quality of research had generally improved. They
would prefer to see fewer 'overnight notes' - sometimes produced in haste
after a big event. They needed more research on medium and smaller companies
and more 'thematic pieces'. Research covering the UK economy was 'least
useful'.
Last year's enthusiasm for pan-European markets had been replaced by a need
for more research on emerging markets.
SG Warburg Securities took the title of top stockbroking research company
for the third year in a row. James Capel reclaimed the number two slot from
NatWest Securities.
Credit Lyonnais Laing and Smith New Court were voted as having shown the
most improvement in quality.
</TEXT>
