<HEADLINE>
FT  02 JUL 93 / BPB gains 52% as peace breaks out on prices
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW TAYLOR, Construction Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
PROFITS of BPB Industries, Europe's biggest plasterboard manufacturer, have
jumped 52 per cent following the end of a price war in the UK, France and
Germany.
Group pre-tax profits rose from Pounds 37.8m to Pounds 57.5m in the 12
months to March. Turnover rose 10 per cent to Pounds 1.12bn.
The UK company has cut its final dividend from 7.25p to 4.8p, as forecast in
February when it raised Pounds 64m in a convertible bond issue. The total
payout is 11.25p.
Mr John Maxwell, chief executive, said BPB had decided to rebase its
dividend 'in view of the unprecedented economic uncertainties facing the
group's main European markets'.
Group pre-tax profits, which four years ago exceeded Pounds 200m, were
unlikely to return to previous levels even when construction markets
recovered, he said. Earnings per share, which rose from 6p to 8.1p, were
less than a third of the 32.2p made in 1988-89.
Mr Maxwell said western European plasterboard prices, which have risen by an
average of 29 per cent since February 1992, were still well below levels
prevailing at the end of the 1980s.
The increases follow the ending of a price war between the three largest
plasterboard producers: BPB, Knauf of Germany and Lafarge-Coppee of France.
This left BPB's share of the European market relatively unscathed at between
50 and 55 per cent. The company's share of the UK market, where it
previously had a near monopoly, has fallen from more than 90 per cent to
about 65 per cent.
Mr Maxwell said that Knauf and Lafarge-Coppee now appeared more interested
in improving profitability than pursuing market share and that further price
rises were likely.
BPB's target was to double its return on sales from 7 to 15 per cent and the
return on capital from 10 to 20 per cent.
Mr Maxwell warned of further job losses as the group sought to cut costs.
Some 700 jobs were axed last year resulting in a redundancy cost of Pounds
11m.
He expected European plasterboard sales to fall over the next 12 months
despite a 'still strong market in Germany' and a faltering recovery in the
UK.
Lex, Page 18
</TEXT>
