<HEADLINE>
FT  02 JUL 93 / Governments may act on Channel tunnel date
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW TAYLOR and ALICE RAWSTHORN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   LONDON, PARIS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
A SUGGESTION that the UK and French governments appoint an independent
mediator to try to resolve the conflict between Eurotunnel and its
contractors over the opening date of the Channel tunnel has been discussed
by the two countries.
The UK transport department confirmed that the suggestion had been raised by
French officials, but said the UK government had no plans to appoint a
mediator. Any such appointment would be a matter for the Bank of England to
decide rather than government.
Contractors are seeking substantial additional payments to cover the cost of
building the tunnel which, including interest payments, has risen from
Pounds 4.8bn in 1987 to approaching Pounds 10bn.
The contractors' claims are already being considered by an independent
disputes panel.
The initiative proposed by the French would seek to get Eurotunnel and its
contractors to agree an opening date rather than try to resolve the payments
issue.
Contractors have said that the project, which had been due to open in May
this year, will not open until next summer unless agreement can be reached.
Eurotunnel in Paris yesterday confirmed that it was in discussions with the
French government over the appointment of a separate mediator to try to
resolve the conflict over the opening date.
The company said the idea of a mediator - or a Monsieur de Bons Offices -
had come from the government. Eurotunnel said it supported the initiative.
</TEXT>
