<HEADLINE>
FT  02 JUL 93 / College lecturers plan action over changes in contracts
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN AUTHERS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
COLLEGE LECTURERS are likely to plan strike action after the introduction of
tough contracts yesterday cutting their holidays in half and adding an hour
to their working day.
The change follows the transfer in April of further education colleges from
local authorities to national government control. The contracts alter terms
and conditions in place for two decades.
Since the switch of control, the College Employers' Forum, which represents
360 further education colleges in England and Wales with 55,000 lecturers,
has sought to establish itself as a tough public sector employer.
Mr Roger Ward, chief executive of the CEF, said the contracts were in line
with requests by Mr Tim Boswell, further and higher education minister, for
employers to 'rapidly introduce' changes in lecturers' conditions.
The contracts, initially only for starters and those lecturers who are
moving colleges or have been promoted, make several changes to the old
arrangement:
The 30-hour working week is abolished and increased to 37 hours (36 in
London).
Holiday entitlement is cut to seven weeks per year, plus statutory holidays,
from 14.
Redundancy notice periods are cut from 12 months to between one and three
months.
Lecturers must gain their principal's permission before taking on any
outside work. Confidentiality agreements must now be signed to prevent
lecturers divulging information about their old departments if they move to
a new college. Lecturers will be barred from moving to companies which
compete with their old college.
Employers say the alterations are to accommodate the changing role of
further education which involves offering part-time courses throughout the
year.
The National Association of Teachers in Further and Higher Education has
refused to negotiate with the CEF if the contracts are on the agenda. Its
conference starts tomorrow and is likely to prepare for strike action.
</TEXT>
