<HEADLINE>
FT  02 JUL 93 / Arts: Today's Television
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER DUNKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Both BBC networks are heavy on repeats. Between 7.30 and 1.10 in the morning
the only non-repeats on BBC1 are Points Of View, the 10-minute letters
programme; the Nine O'Clock News, and Today At Wimbledon (10.25). The only
programme on commercial tv which attracts me is Athletics from Edinburgh,
where Britain meets the USA. There is an hour on ITV from 8.00 and another
hour on C4 from 8.55. Friday once again proves a good night for radio, and
BBC radio has clearly discovered what those of us born in Scarborough have
always known: that this, the world's first seaside resort, is the centre of
the universe. At 8.05 Radio 4 broadcasts Any Questions? from Scarborough. At
9.50 Radio 3 offers Virtuoso Italian Baroque Chamber Music from the Spa
Grand Hall. And at 10.00 the Radio 2 Arts Programme visits Scarborough to
discuss Alan Ayckbourn and to interview Ian Carmichael about his role in the
second series of 'Strathblair'. There is also the second of the Reith
Lectures (9.20 Radio 3) by Edward Said and, from another seaside town,
Reaping The Elements: The Art Of St Ives (10.45 Radio 3).
