<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT933-16689</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-DGBCVAC8FT</PROFILE>
<DATE>930702
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  02 JUL 93 / Parliament and Politics: Letters show a persistent Mates
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL CASSELL
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE PUBLICATION of edited letters yesterday between Mr Michael Mates and the
government's most senior law officers paints an extraordinary picture of a
lone minister increasingly convinced of a conspiracy to damn Mr Asil Nadir.
In representations to two attorneys-general over the past 18 months Mr Mates
appeared to have become increasingly consumed with the alleged treatment of
Mr Nadir and determined to expose what he believed to be a catalogue of
abuse by the authorities.
In spite of repeated denials from Sir Patrick Mayhew and Sir Nicholas Lyell,
his successor as attorney-general, Mr Mates alleged numerous intimidatory
and improper acts by the Serious Fraud Office and also claimed collusion
between the SFO and the Inland Revenue.
Throughout, Mr Mates suggested that Mr Nadir, in spite of his departure from
the UK, remained anxious to return to the UK in order to clear his name.
The most startling claim in his personal campaign to protect Mr Nadir's
rights involved the suggestion that the fugitive businessman's empire, which
dominates the economy of northern Cyprus, was at the centre of an
intelligence service plot to destabilise the country. His fears on this
front rose when he heard that similar allegations might be included in a
proposed television programme.
Much of the correspondence published yesterday covers ground covered in the
statement which Mr Mates managed, in spite of the reluctance of the Speaker,
to make earlier this week in the Commons. It omits, however, all reference
to his allegations of a conspiracy to pervert the course of justice by
bribing Mr Justice Tucker, the Nadir trial judge.
The letters date from September 20 1991, following a meeting the previous
day between Mr Mates and Sir Patrick. The MP complained that privileged
documents removed from Mr Nadir's office were opened, contrary to an
agreement, by the SFO and demanded that it 'tell the whole truth' about the
matter.
He also accused the SFO of arranging publicity for raids on Polly Peck
International, Mr Nadir's company, and of excessive delays which continued
to deny the businessman the chance to state his case in court.
Sir Patrick rejected the idea of any improper motives and said that, on all
the counts raised by Mr Mates, he was satisfied the SFO had acted carefully
and responsibly.
Last December Mr Mates met Sir Nicholas, now attorney-general, to press his
case that Mr Nadir was being unjustly treated and first raised the
possibility that intelligence services might be involved. He complained that
the businessman had been arrested eight times without warning, in spite of
meeting all his bail conditions.
Sir Nicholas also categorically denied the assertion that police officers,
SFO staff or anyone else connected with the Nadir investigation had gone to
Cyprus.
Mr Mates finally met the attorney-general on May 10, when Sir Nicholas
assured the minister that each issue he had raised had been examined very
carefully. Undeterred, Mr Mates pressed home his concerns about the conduct
of the case.
One June 8 Sir Nicholas made a further attempt to ease some of Mr Mates'
concerns, re-emphasising that claims of collusion to undermine Polly Peck
were unsupported by any evidence. Mr Mates, frustrated by his lack of
progress but determined not to let the subject drop, was reaching the end of
his ministerial career.
</TEXT>
