<HEADLINE>
FT  02 JUL 93 / Parliament and Politics: Howard seeks new drive on crime
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IVOR OWEN and RALPH ATKINS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A NEW campaign to enlist support from the public in combating the crime wave
was launched by Mr Michael Howard, the home secretary, in the Commons last
night.
Opening a debate on law and order, he said: 'I want to channel the public's
energies in a constructive way to build a new, stronger and more effective
alliance against crime.'
Tory backbenchers joined with the minister in seeking to counter the impact
made by Mr Tony Blair, Labour's shadow home secretary, in his recent call
for a crusade against crime.
Mr Howard said he wanted to create an atmosphere in which criminals were
'frightened' and not members of the public.
He also wanted to make local communities feel that 'we can act together to
do something about crime'.
Mr Howard promised: 'We will do that by taking a long-term approach to
crime, by attacking it from every quarter'.
However, the government may be facing embarrassment after the Tory candidate
in the Christchurch by-election sought to outflank his Liberal Democrat
rival by setting crime and capital punishment at the top of his agenda -
even though the home secretary opposes hanging.
Mr Robert Hayward yesterday angered Mr Paddy Ashdown, Liberal Democrat
leader, by launching a survey of public opinion in Christchurch on capital
punishment.
The Tory campaign team's high-risk strategy could succeed in diverting
attention from disquiet over government policies. But Mr Hayward could
embarrass ministers, most of whom are opposed to hanging.
During the Commons debate yesterday Mr Howard, regarded as being on the Tory
right wing, said he had previously supported capital punishment but was now
opposed because of the initial failure of the appeals procedures in cases
such as that of the six men wrongly convicted of the Birmingham pub
bombings.
No date has been set for the Christchurch by-election, caused by the death
of Mr Robert Adley, the Conservative MP who had a 23,000 majority at the
last general election. Yet later this month is still regarded as the most
likely date.
</TEXT>
