<HEADLINE>
FT  02 JUL 93 / Patten lists tight curbs for student unions
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN AUTHERS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR JOHN PATTEN, the education secretary, announced yesterday that student
unions are to be made voluntary organisations. They will be barred from
using public funds for political campaigning.
Proposals he intends to include in an education bill in the next session of
parliament would limit public funding to a small group of core activities.
Fees to affiliate to political organisations, including the National Union
of Students, would not be paid by the state. Unions would have to ask
students to opt into them by paying individual fees.
Mr Patten said: 'Student unions should be more accountable and fully
representative. We shall therefore provide for institutions to develop and
implement codes of practice governing the conduct and behaviour of their
campus unions.
'Our intention is not to impede students' activities. It is to limit the
purposes for which stud-ent unions can spend public money.'
Dr David Harrison of Exeter University, who chairs the Committee of
Vice-chancellors and Principals, said the proposals were 'a steam hammer to
crack a nut'.
He attacked the decision to limit students' unions to a specific list of
activities. He said: 'The CVCP has told ministers that it is extremely
difficult to define core activities in this way. It is very curious that the
government's list does not include academic, artistic and cultural
activities, but does include sports and catering.'
Dr Harrison also criticised the three-month consultation period, which
starts just as university terms are ending, and will end when students start
to return in October.
Ms Lorna Fitzsimons, president of the National Union of Students, agreed
with Dr Harrison. She said: 'It's a very expensive bone for Mr Patten to
toss to the right wing and save his popularity.'
The students' union at the London School of Economics also attacked the
proposals. An official said it might prevent unions from taking part in
'such vital areas as rag charity fund-raising'. It would also put an end to
the LSE union's policy of paying for scholarships for those in need.
</TEXT>
