<HEADLINE>
FT  02 JUL 93 / ITV may take legal action to change timing of News At Ten
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RAYMOND SNODDY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE ITV companies have not yet ruled out a legal challenge to the insistence
of the Independent Television Commission that News At Ten has to stay in its
traditional time slot.
Mr Greg Dyke, chairman of the ITV companies, told the Commons national
heritage committee yesterday that ITV had obtained a legal opinion which
disagreed with the ITC's interpretation of the law.
On Wednesday the commission wrote to all ITV chairmen warning that the
companies would be in breach of their licences if the programme was moved
without permission.
Mr Dyke told the committee: 'We will not rush off to law. We will not rush
into a decision.' It is clear, however, that challenging the ITC's
interpretation of the law will be one of the options at Monday's meeting of
the ITV council, when the News At Ten issue is discussed.
Mr Dyke, who is also chief executive of London Weekend Television, told MPs
he did not believe his company was commited to running News at Ten in its
present slot. The commitment, he believed, was to run a main news in prime
time, which the ITC has defined as 6.30pm to 10.30pm.
Mr Andrew Quinn, chief executive of the ITV Network Centre, set out the
commercial case for moving News At Ten.
At 10pm, Mr Quinn said, BBC, Channel 4 and BSkyB were eating into ITV
ratings. In May an ITV audience share of 46 per cent at 9pm fell to 35 per
cent at 10pm - and the audience was older and less up-market.
Mr Quinn added that advertisers were prepared to pay a premium of up to 100
per cent to advertise in programmes such as Inspector Morse instead of News
At Ten.
The audience for News At Ten is volatile - in the week ending June 6 the
audience ranged from 9.8m to 3.7m when scheduled against the BBC's 999.
Mr Leslie Hill, chairman of Central, told MPs that this year ITV would pay
the government a total of Pounds 367m. Under the old levy system the total
would have been Pounds 150m.
On the News At Ten issue, MPs expressed surprise that ITV was trying to make
such a fundamental change only six months into new franchises.
</TEXT>
