<HEADLINE>
FT  02 JUL 93 / BBC expected to announce doubling of operating surplus
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RAYMOND SNODDY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE BBC is in a stronger financial position than widely reported. The
1992-93 annual report, to be published at the end of this month, is expected
to show a doubled operating surplus.
Last year the corporation had an operating surplus of about Pounds 30m.
Potential overspends on programme making of Pounds 15.9m in 1992-93 and
Pounds 38m in the previous year have been compensated for by savings in the
overall budget.
The BBC is, however, still in deficit because of the cost of a planned
restructuring programme. The four-year programme - which has one more year
to run - and its associated redundancy payments are costing the BBC a total
of Pounds 215m.
The corporation, which has licence fee income of about Pounds 1.4bn a year,
has managed to remain within its borrowing limits of Pounds 200m.
Mr Rodney Baker-Bates, the new finance director of the BBC who is former
group finance director of Midland Bank, has asked for further cuts in
corporation overheads to put more money into programmes.
Mr Baker-Bates is looking for a 10 per cent cut in the 1994-95 financial
year in the budget of the BBC's central administration, which accounts for
about 7 per cent of total BBC expenditure.
A budget cut of 3 per cent is being levied on the rest of the BBC. As a
result an estimated extra Pounds 50m is expected to be directed into
programme making.
Mr Barker-Bates plans to issue budgetary guidelines covering the period up
to the end of 1996 - when the BBC royal charter runs out.
The government has commissioned consultants from Touche Ross to check on BBC
efforts to become more efficient.
The Touche Ross report is expected to inform government decisions on the
licence fee until the end of the charter period. The BBC hopes that the
licence fee will continue to be linked to retail prices.
'I think the BBC has a good story to tell and we can defend our corner,'
said Mr Baker-Bates.
</TEXT>
