<HEADLINE>
FT  02 JUL 93 / After Kalms' speech - vigilance or vigilantes?: The Dixons
chief's suggestion that stores will have to become fortresses to fight crime
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NEIL BUCKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
IN SPAIN, licensed vigilantes carrying revolvers are employed to guard some
retail chains. In the US stores display signs boasting their prices are low
not because they are such efficient retailers, but because 'we have theft
under control'.
The suggestion on Tuesday by Dixons chairman Mr Stanley Kalms that UK
retailers might have to adopt vigilante tactics and turn their stores into
'fortresses' to deal with a rising tide of crime may not have been welcomed
by all retailers. But its substance met with little disagreement.
The British Retail Consortium believes crime costs UK retailers at least
Pounds 2.5bn a year. The true figure may be much higher because many
retailers do not bother to report small crimes as there is little chance of
getting a conviction. Marks and Spencer, the UK's biggest clothing and food
retailer, says the problem is 'the equivalent of a Brink's Mat bullion
robbery every four days'.
M&amp;S says: 'Some people think retail crime is relatively insignificant
because it is seen as victimless. But it makes victims out of all of us
because we are paying for it every time we do our shopping.' The company
says customers are paying up to 1p out of every Pounds 1 to cover the costs
of crime.
Mr Kalms focused on the problem of organised crime, describing how
'alternative entrepreneurs' robbed shops, often through ramraiding, then
sold the goods through an elaborate network of 'squatter stores' and
car-boot sales.
But shops suffer from a range of problems, from petty pilfering - sometimes
by their own staff - and casual shoplifting, to attacks on staff and,
increasingly, armed robbery. Credit-card and cheque fraud are also thought
to cost retailers up to Pounds 300m a year.
A survey in 1991 by Touche Ross, the management consultancy, found retailers
spending an average of 0.3 per cent of turnover on security measures. For
large retailers with turnovers of billions of pounds that represents tens of
millions of pounds of investment in security. It also found that stores were
increasingly investing in sophisticated computer systems, video equipment
and alarms rather than relying on store detectives.
Mr Kalms said crime and investment in measures to prevent it were costing
Dixons Pounds 20m a year. M&amp;S says it is losing Pounds 30m a year through
crime, and spending Pounds 21m on combating it.
The subject is a sensitive one, some retailers being wary of creating too
much of a fuss, or making their security measures too visible, for fear of
intimidating shoppers.
M&amp;S, however, says its own research suggests shoppers are reassured by
visible security measures such as cameras and guards.
It may have been frustration at the unwillingness of many retailers to talk
openly about the problem that prompted Mr Kalms to speak out. But some
believe he has gone too far.
Mr Frank Pegg of Volumatic Systems, a manufacturer of security devices with
30 years' experience of advising retailers, says: 'Things are getting worse
in the retail trade, and we all appreciate that today's crime is tomorrow's
price rise, but I don't think what Mr Kalms said was helpful. To say British
shopkeepers are being forced to adopt vigilante tactics is a bit much, and
may put off shoppers.'
One large store chain suggests Mr Kalms has 'overstated the case'. Retailers
also feel he is wrong to criticise the police.
Certainly, his remarks did not go down well with the Metropolitan Police,
who described his jibe that the police were little more than a
data-collection agency as 'absolute nonsense'.
Most retailers say they do not agree with his vision of 'vigilantes'
patrollingshops and shopping centres.
Mr William Hucklesby, head of group security at Sears, and chairman of the
security committee of the Oxford Street Association, says it is 'vital that
retailers should work in partnership with the police'. He agrees that the
police need more resources. Action is being taken at an industry level to
deal with the problem.
The British Retail Consortium has launched a special initiative on crime
following a meeting of retailers in January with Mr Ian Jack, Home Office
minister.
The meeting agreed to fund jointly a director for the initiative - recently
named as Mr John Burrows, a partner in Morgan Harris Burrows, a consultancy
specialising in crime risk management, and a former security adviser to
Dixons. The initiative plans to develop a database on the extent of retail
crime, something on which neither the Home Office nor the police now has
reliable information.
By monitoring the success of the initiative, it hopes to produce
recommendations on best practice for consortium members. The security
industry, meanwhile, is developing ever more sophisticated methods of
dealing with retail crime, and has seen a big increase in its business.
The British Security Industry Association says total turnover of member
companies grew from Pounds 1.1bn in 1989 to Pounds 1.4bn in 1992. Spending
on closed-circuit television equipment rose from Pounds 37m to Pounds 64m.
In addition to physical barriers such as laminated glass, reinforced
shutters and car-traps to deter ramraiding and smash-and-grab raids, stores
can choose from a range of in-store technology.
Modern closed-circuit television systems can produce a high-definition image
of suspect shoppers even at considerable distances.
Radio-based product tags which activate alarms at shop exits have long been
common in the fashion business, but are increasingly being replaced by
electromagnetic tabs which can be incorporated into bar codes on even the
smallest items and deactivated when the item is scanned at the check-out.
But Mr Grenville Peacock, chief executive of the Bentalls department store
chain in south-east England, warns that tagging can be of little use against
the hardened criminals who now attack shops.
'Shop crime is becoming much more blatant, much more open, much more daring.
It's difficult to deal with because you are exposing your people to being
thumped - or worse.'
</TEXT>
<XX>
