<HEADLINE>
FT  02 JUL 93 / Seven shops - three raids a week: And teenage black
marketeers send 7-year-olds in to shoplift for them
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRIS TIGHE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
ONE MAN who has no hesitation in supporting the views of Mr Stanley Kalms is
Mr Leo Gillen, Hartlepool's largest independent newsagent. He has seven
shops in the town and they are the target for an average of three attempted
break-ins every week.
'What he's saying is basically right,' says Mr Gillen. 'The government is
not addressing the issue of law and order properly. Retailers are having to
fight crime themselves.'
Security devices at Mr Gillen's shops, which stock a range of goods, consume
10 per cent of his net profit.
All have steel doors and shutters with security locks and anti-ramraid
bollards in front. They also have dedicated phone lines to a burglar alarm
company - alarm bells proved useless when the thieves put them out of action
by swamping them with foam.
Most of the shops have closed-circuit television and all have vigilant
staff. But they still suffer from organised thieving, especially of tights,
hair mousse, coffee, tinned tuna, salmon and bacon. A black market exists
for these products. The hair products are sold to small hairdressers, says
Mr Gillen, and the other items are sold door-to-door. 'You have youths of 17
and 18 who send children of seven or eight into the shops to steal because
nothing happens to them. It's a real problem.'
The problems, which Mr Gillen has noticed accelerating in the past five to
six years, extend to harassment of employees. 'You get children throwing
stones at the staff and abusing them,' he says.
Three weeks ago an employee quit because of problems with youths. Only this
week two teenagers in balaclavas, carrying water pistols, walked into two of
Mr Gillen's shops. 'We didn't know whether it was an attempted raid or a
joke,' he says. In one incident youths pulled down and locked the security
shutters of one shop, trapping the staff inside.
Mr Gillen also owns a pub and fish-and-chip shop in Hartlepool. His annual
turnover totals Pounds 5.5m.
He is chairman of the Owton Manor police steering committee, a community
consultation panel on one of Hartlepool's hard-up estates. The committee has
helped, he says, but the problem goes deeper than anything police or
magistrates can solve.
'I feel there are too many people cast out of society with the high
unemployment figures,' he says. In Hartlepool, for a long time one of
Britain's unemployment blackspots, many 15-year-olds have grown up in
families where nobody works, he says.
This breeds a lack of aspiration. 'When you have people running around
lawless they have no comprehension of moral law.'
</TEXT>
