<HEADLINE>
FT  02 JUL 93 / BMA votes out moderate leader
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALAN PIKE, Social Affairs Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
DR JEREMY Lee-Potter, the moderate leader of the British Medical Association
who re-established relationships with the government after confrontation
over the National Health Service reforms, yesterday lost his post as
chairman of the BMA council.
He fell to a challenge to his leadership by 36 votes to 17 at a council
meeting at the end of the BMA conference in Torquay. His successor is Dr
Alexander Macara, 61, a Bristol University consultant lecturer in public
health medicine and former chairman of the BMA medical ethics committee.
Dr Lee-Potter became chairman three years ago at a time of open hostility
between the BMA and government. He accepted the reality of health reforms
and returned the association to dialogue with the government.
His conciliatory stance never found favour with sections of the BMA. As the
conference made clear, many doctors continue to believe that government
reforms are undermining the principles of the NHS and aggravating funding
problems.
Dr Macara, who wants an early meeting with health secretary Mrs Virginia
Bottomley, denied he would be more confrontational but added there would be
a change of style.
He said: 'I fear that the secretary of state gets false reassurances from
her courtiers who tell her what she wants to hear. We have to have
consistent and vigorous proposals to persuade her to re-examine the evidence
for change.'
</TEXT>
