<HEADLINE>
FT  02 JUL 93 / Government sells property concerns
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By VANESSA HOULDER, Property Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE SALE of part of the Property Services Agency, which manages the
government's property estate, was announced yesterday.
The government has sold two of the agency's five building-management
businesses to a joint venture between Amec, the contractor, and Pell
Frischmann, an engineering and project-management consultancy. The sale
figure was a net Pounds 11.4m over the next four years.
The joint venture has bought the BM South East and BM South &amp; West
businesses. The government has guaranteed work worth Pounds 400m during the
next five years.
The Department of the Environment said it would meet the cost of
redundancies over the next five years, up to an agreed figure. Many of the
3,300 staff are expected to seek redundancy although Amec said it would seek
to persuade the entire staff to transfer to the new company.
The sale of the remaining three building-management businesses is expected
within the next few weeks.
Their sale will complete the privatisation of the Property Services Agency.
The sell-off began last year with the sale of its project division to
Tarmac, the construction and building materials group.
Mr Trevor Osborne, chairman of Speyhawk, the property company which went
into receivership in May, will be chairman of the joint venture.
