<HEADLINE>
FT  02 JUL 93 / Foreign investors prefer Britain
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL CASSELL, Business Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE UK continues to account for about a third of inward investment into
European Community countries although the number of projects involved has
fallen for the second year running.
Government figures published yesterday show overseas investors sanctioned
303 new capital expenditure projects last year, creating or safeguarding
more than 56,000 jobs - 5,000 more than in the previous year.
The biggest inward investor into the UK last year was the US, with 126
projects involving new investment, expansion or acquisition. Germany was
second, followed by Japan and Switzerland.
The Invest in Britain Bureau, part of the Department of Trade and Industry,
said it could not place a value on 1992 inward investment because some
companies had not disclosed details. New capital investment in the previous
year was estimated at Pounds 1.3bn.
The peak year for inward investment into the UK was 1990, when 350 projects
were started, with the total falling to 332 in 1991. It is thought, however,
that the UK is still taking about one third of EC inward investment.
Announcing details, Baroness Denton, small firms minister, said the UK was
maintaining its position as the preferred investment location in Europe for
companies based outside the EC. Many of them were making an increasingly
important contribution to UK exporting efforts.
She said that in spite of rising competition in the EC to attract inward
investors Britain remained the 'number one choice' for US and Japanese
investors.
The minister said that the UK had 'stolen a march' on France and Germany,
which had initially discouraged foreign investment.
US and Japanese companies are making about 40 per cent of all EC-based
investment in the UK, with the electronics and automotive sectors among the
most active. Regional selective assistance of Pounds 103m was made available
to inward-investing companies in 1992.
The bureau calculates that although overseas companies investing in the UK
still represent only 1 per cent of UK business, they account for 16 per cent
of UK manufacturing jobs, 22 per cent of net output and 27 per cent of net
capital expenditure.
Mr Tim Eggar, energy minister, yesterday announced an Pounds 8.25m regional
selective assistance grant to Europa Magnetic Corporation of Taiwan, which
is to locate its European headquarters at Cramlington in Northumberland. The
floppy disk assembly operation, to serve European and US markets, will
create 550 jobs.
</TEXT>
