<HEADLINE>
FT  02 JUL 93 / Stronger pound may have the shine taken off it / Assessing
why sterling has been climbing
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER MARSH and GILLIAN TETT
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE pound is no longer the sickly weakling of nine months ago. But talk of
it entering a new phase of upswing against other important currencies is
probably overdone.
Helped by the Bundesbank's cut in interest rates and a Treasury statement
signalling no immediate easing in UK monetary policy, the pound yesterday
consolidated its recent good run against the D-Mark.
Last night sterling closed in London up 1 3/4 pfennigs on the day at
DM2.5625, its highest level since last September's devaluation.
Because of a less robust performance against other currencies, notably the
dollar and yen, the pound has looked slightly less perky when measured by
the Bank of England's trade-weighted index.
It closed last night on this index at 80.9, slightly below its best level
this year about two months ago, but comfortably up on its historic low of
75.7 in February.
An important aspect which will almost certainly restrain the pound's rise is
that any further strengthening would go down badly with manufacturers. They
are flavour of the month at the Treasury in the light of comments by Mr
Kenneth Clarke, the chancellor, that he wants to make the department more
sympathetic to industry.
Echoing the concerns of big manufacturers that any new increase in the
pound's value would reduce the competitiveness of UK goods and choke off
encouraging signs of export growth, Mr Neil Johnson, director-general of the
Engineering Employers' Federation, said he 'views with concern' the general
drift upward by sterling.
As a result of such sentiments and acting in concert with the Treasury, the
Bank of England has in recent weeks discreetly sold sterling both to reduce
its value and boost its heavily depleted foreign currency reserves.
But sterling's upward movement has been unmistakable. The reasons include:
Better growth prospects this year for Britain than for most European
countries.
Strong buying by Japanese institutional investors, many of which, especially
given the high recent value of the yen, view the pound as cheap.
The weakness of the D-Mark, resulting from concern about the fragile state
of the German economy and speculation about cuts in German interest rates -
duly served up yesterday.
Heavy purchases in the past month by overseas institutions of gilt-edged
securities which, notwithstanding the relative lack of success of this
week's big gilts auction, have helped to push up the pound.
Mr Clarke's ruling out of cuts in base rates in the near term unless the
economy shows a sudden slide.
Many City economists believe sterling is unlikely to rise above DM2.6 by the
end of the summer.
Also the pound may find it hard to sustain its rise yesterday against the
dollar, which was sparked mainly by a US report indicating doubts about the
strength of US industrial growth. Sterling was quoted last night in London
at Dollars 1.5085, up 1 1/2 cents.
Mr Brian Martin, senior economist at Citibank in London, said there were
still 'some pitfalls' ahead for the UK economy which might constrain
sterling. He was sceptical about the note of euphoria which has crept into
discussion about the pound, pointing out that growth in consumer spending
might be extremely fragile.
Mr Steve Hannah, chief economist at IBJ International in London, said Mr
Clarke might ease monetary policy if sterling's growth made life more
difficult for manufacturers. 'The perception that Mr Clarke is more growth
orientated than his predecessor has boosted market feeling that interest
rates might be cut if sterling surged.'
Mr George Magnus, economist at SG Warburg Securities, said the weakness of
the D-Mark might soon pass. Any strengthening in the German currency would
take some of the shine off sterling.
</TEXT>
