<HEADLINE>
FT  02 JUL 93 / Dozen directors earn Pounds 1m a year
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DIANE SUMMERS, Labour Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
IN MORE THAN 50 quoted companies at least one director earned Pounds 500,000
or more last year, while a dozen received Pounds 1m or just under.
The figures are revealed today in an analysis of company annual reports for
1992.
The median increase in the highest paid directors' earnings was 5.5 per
cent, says the survey by Monks Partnership, a pay research group.
At the same time, many top executives in the largest companies took an
earnings cut. In more than a quarter of companies with a turnover greater
than Pounds 50m, the highest paid directors' earnings were reduced. Overall
the rate of top earnings increases continued to fall.
Mr Tony Vernon-Harcourt from Monks said it was important to view the
increases in context. 'Most companies reporting to November 1992 or later
will have set base earnings changes for their executives in October or
November 1991. At that time the underlying growth in average earnings was
7.25 per cent, so an increase of 5 per cent would be looked on as perfectly
fair and reasonable.'
Performance bonuses, as well as base pay, are included in the survey figures
 -not all companies currently separate the two in their annual reports.
Listed companies reporting on years ending after June 30 1993 will be
required to state the extent to which they have complied with the Cadbury
best-practice code.
One of the code's requirements is that 'separate figures should be given for
salary and performance-related elements and the basis on which performance
is measured should be explained'.
Monks said that, where companies now disclose the presence of incentive
plans, 'there appears to be a reasonable correlation between the payment of
an annual cash incentive and company results'.
Where it seemed there was a mismatch, it was often because of the payment of
longer-term incentives which were dependent on the achievement of pre-set
targets over three or more years, the company said. However, it added:
'There is no doubt that, in some cases, there is no discernible, or
declared, relationship between individual rewards and corporate
performance'.
UK Board Earnings, July edition. Monks Partnership, Debden Green, Saffron
Walden, Essex CB11 3LX. Pounds 125.
</TEXT>
