<HEADLINE>
FT  02 JUL 93 / Spraying of oil slicks defended
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
THE Department of Transport defended the practice of aerial spraying to
counter coastal oil pollution when the government's contingency plans came
under scrutiny at the Donaldson inquiry this week.
The hearing is looking at the wider implications of the Braer tanker
disaster off Shetland this year. There has been evidence that questions the
government's emergency strategy which relies on aerial spraying as the first
line of defence.
Questioned by Lord Donaldson, Mr Chris Harris, head of the Department of
Transport's Marine Pollution Control Unit, insisted there was international
agreement that chemical dispersants were an effective way of breaking up oil
spills.
The inquiry continues.
