<HEADLINE>
FT  02 JUL 93 / Iraq wants to discuss lifting of sanctions
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JAMES WHITTINGTON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BAGHDAD
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
IRAQ'S Deputy Prime Minister Tariq Aziz said last night he believed Iraq had
done enough to warrant the lifting of sanctions against it.
In an interview with the US Cable News Network, CNN, he said his government
wanted to open 'technical, legal and objective' discussions with the UN
Security Council about all outstanding issues with a view to easing
sanctions soon.
He went on to express Iraq's fear that even if every detail of Gulf War
ceasefire resolution 687 was implemented, the 33-month-old sanctions might
not be lifted. 'We don't have a solid promise that sanctions will be lifted
when all the resolutions are implemented,' he said. He called for a review
by the Security Council to examine exactly where Iraq stood and discussion
of all the remaining issues.
Mr Aziz's comments come five days after the US launched a missile attack
against Baghdad intelligence headquarters which killed six civilians and
wounded many others. He decried the attack as 'totally unjustified' and said
Iraq wanted 'a quiet and normal relationship with the US'.
Referring to the 'ceasefire' announced by President Saddam Hussein on
January 19 after the previous allied air attack on Baghdad, he said Iraq had
'shown good intentions' which had been rejected by the US. In contrast to
more belligerent statements by Iraqi officials this week, the minister said
Iraq would not 'condone any acts of aggression' in retaliation against the
US strike.
Meanwhile, there seemed little development on the deadlock between the UN
and Iraq over the UN demand to install cameras at two ballistic missile
sites outside Baghdad.
</TEXT>
