<HEADLINE>
FT  02 JUL 93 / US backs Japanese, German UN bid
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL LITTLEJOHNS
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE US yesterday formally supported the admission of Germany and Japan to
permanent membership of the UN Security Council, but Britain cautioned
against 'precipitate action'.
Noting that the 15-nation council had finally assumed its intended position
'at the centre of world affairs', Britain argued there was no pressing need
for change, although 'success should be built upon'.
While backing the well known aspirations of Bonn and Tokyo to join the
present five founding permanent members, the US added a caveat that they
must be prepared to be active in global peace and security activities. That
would involve being ready to provide UN peacekeepers, for which both
countries would need constitutional amendments.
However, not all members would welcome an increased military role for the
former second world war enemy states, whose defeat led to the creation of
the UN.
The US and British statements responded to a resolution requesting members'
views on 'Equitable representation on and increase in the membership of the
Security Council'. The issue will be debated by the General Assembly later
this year.
While backing Germany and Japan for permanent seats, the US emphasised that
the current big five - also including France, Russia and China - had
political and economic influence and the capacity and will to enhance global
security through peace keeping and other activities. 'Their status on the
council should remain unaltered.'
Thus, fears that the US might eventually be willing to see Britain and
France superseded, as declining powers, were emphatically allayed.
In reply, Britain made no mention of Germany and Japan but stressed the
present council had been able to respond rapidly to international crises and
permitted equitable representation from all regions working with the
permanent members. No fewer than 70 resolutions were adopted last year alone
and 60,000 UN peace keepers were deployed.
</TEXT>
