</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
TAIWAN yesterday approved a draft economic programme and a package of
measures to promote private investment in manufacturing and to stem the flow
of capital to China.
The draft, prepared by the Council for Economic Planning and Development
(CEPD), highlighted the sluggish state of manufacturing and emphasised the
need to promote private investment.
Superficially, Taiwan's economy seems strong. Average real economic growth
between 1988 and 1992 of 6.7 per cent compared to the average world rate of
2.4 per cent over the period. Government planners forecast a rise of 6.33
per cent for 1993.
However, the growth in fixed capital investment has been declining from
between 25 and 30 per cent of GDP in the early 1980s to 21.6 per cent of GDP
over the past five years. Private capital investment has been rising by an
