<HEADLINE>
FT  02 JUL 93 / Accountants fight ruling over Polly Peck work
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW JACK
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
TWO top accountants are fighting a temporary suspension ruling preventing
them undertaking new insolvency work, triggered by their appointment as
administrators to Polly Peck International.
Mr Michael Jordan and Mr Richard Stone of Coopers &amp; Lybrand, the accountancy
firm, are being scrutinised for breaches in ethical guidelines by accepting
the appointment when their firm had conducted work for PPI and Mr Asil
Nadir, its fugitive former chairman.
The work included offshore trust management and personal tax advice to Mr
Nadir, and advice to the company in the late 1980s on accounting methods for
its substantial foreign currency earnings which were quite legal but boosted
assets and profits.
The details emerged as Mr George Staple, head of the Serious Fraud Office,
backed its handling of the prosecution against Mr Nadir. In a BBC television
interview, he said defendants in large fraud trials 'are not short of
resources and use all means at their disposal for their defence'. At
Westminster there remained more general concern about the SFO. The
attorney-general, Sir Nicholas Lyell, was said to have raised with Mr Staple
the question of whether the SFO gave the media advance information about
arrests.
In further fall-out after the resignation speech of Mr Michael Mates, the
former Northern Ireland minister, on Tuesday, Labour called for a statement
from Mr Kenneth Clarke, the chancellor, on the alleged breach of
confidentiality by a senior Inland Revenue investigator in referring to the
SFO the affairs of Mr Nadir. The Revenue said last night that the allegation
was 'complete news to us'.
Mr Stone, head of corporate finance at Coopers &amp; Lybrand, and Mr Jordan,
head of the insolvency arm, were last October each fined the then maximum
Pounds 1,000 by the Institute of Chartered Accountants in England and Wales
for breaching guidelines stating insolvency practitioners should not be
appointed to a company with which their firm had 'a continuing professional
relationship'.
The matter was taken up by the insolvency licensing committee of the
institute, which met in secret but it is believed to have resolved to
recommend a temporary suspension on some new insolvency appointments by the
two men.
Coopers &amp; Lybrand appealed, and a review committee chaired by Mr Clive
Parritt, senior partner of accountants Baker Tilly, has now made a judgment
on the appeal, which is expected to be made public on Monday.
Reports, Page 12
</TEXT>
