<HEADLINE>
FT  01 JUL 93 / International Company News: TV network names founding
investors
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By BRUCE JACQUES
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   SYDNEY
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
SEVEN Network, the Australian broadcasting company formerly controlled by Mr
Christopher Skase, has confirmed its planned public float will have News
Corporation and Australian telecommunications group Telecom as founding
shareholders.
Mr Ivan Deveson, Seven Network chairman, said yesterday News Corporation,
the international media group, would hold a 15 per cent interest in the
company and Telecom, the Australian Government-owned telephone group, 10 per
cent.
He said News and Telecom would be entitled to nominate one director each to
the Seven board, but no nominations had yet been received.
Seven, which had been in the hands of its bankers following the collapse of
Mr Skase's Qintex empire, has circulated a draft prospectus for the float,
likely to seek between Dollars A600m (USDollars 402.7m) and Dollars A725m.
The prospectus is believed to price Seven Network shares at just over eight
times forecast earnings for 1994. The offering is expected in August and
analysts said last night the presence of News and Telecom would make the
public marketing task easier.
The float marks a return to metropolitan television in Australia by News
Corporation, which sold its stake in the rival Ten Network in the 1980s to
Westfield, the Australian property investment group.
For Telecom, the investment would be its first in a large television
network.
</TEXT>
