<HEADLINE>
FT  01 JUL 93 / International Company News: Tighter US employee options rule
nearer
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KAREN ZAGOR
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
A CONTROVERSIAL accoun-ting rule change proposed by the US Financial
Accounting Standards Board (FASB), which would force companies to disclose
the value of options granted to employees and subtract them from profits,
yesterday moved one step closer to becoming reality when FASB published its
exposure draft of the new rule.
FASB, a private sector body which sets standards for the accounting
industry, came under fire from business groups in April when it set out its
proposal to force companies to recognise stock options and other stock-based
compensation rewards as an expense.
Yesterday's draft was essentially unchanged from the board's earlier
proposal.
FASB has asked to receive comments on the proposal by December 31. It will
then hold public hearings on the issues.
A final ruling will be issued after the public hearings.
Although companies will not be required to take charges against earnings
until 1997, they will have to provide note disclosures starting in 1994,
including disclosure of the effect on net income and earnings per share as
if the new recognition requirements had been adopted.
Mr Dennis Beresford, FASB chairman, said the delay should help employers
become familiar with using option-pricing models and for financial statement
users to become accustomed to the new information.
'It will give employers time to consider whether to change their stock-based
compensation plans, the design of which may have been heavily influenced by
current accounting requirements.'
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>USZ  United States of America.
</CN>
<XX>
