<HEADLINE>
FT  01 JUL 93 / International Company News: Ryder System to spin off its
aviation business
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NIKKI TAIT
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
RYDER SYSTEM, the Miami-based transportation group, yesterday announced
plans to spin off its aviation business as a separately-quoted company and
take a net second-quarter restructuring charge of Dollars 169.4m. The plan
involves a large jet turbine overhaul shop in Prestwick, Scotland, bought
from British Caledonian in 1986.
Existing Ryder shareholders will be offered shares in the aviation company
by way of a tax-free distribution of stock. The new aviation group will take
in Ryder Airline Services, Ryder Aviall and Inventory Locator Service, and
will be based in Dallas. Included in its assets will be the Prestwick
facility, which employs about 800 and works on General Electric engines for
the likes of British Airways, Continental, USAir and British Midland.
Ryder's aviation business is sizeable. The company claims to be the world's
largest independent supplier of turbine aircraft engine repair services and
the biggest distributor of aviation parts and supplies.
Although it plans to shed some peripheral operations - Ryder Aviall's
business aviation and helicopter engine repair business, its aircraft and
terminal services operation at Dallas's Love Field, and a sales unit in
Miami - the new company would have had revenues of Dollars 1.2bn in 1992,
and assets, at end-1992, of Dollars 1.2bn.
Profits from the aviation interests, however, fell last year - a trend
blamed on lower demand, but which continued in the first quarter of 1993.
About Dollars 500m of debt - just over a quarter of the total at Ryder -
attaches to the aviation interests, and will transfer to the demerged
entity.
Demergers have become increasingly popular in the US recently, as companies
have attempted to generate investor interest by reshaping themselves.
Yesterday, Ryder claimed that the deal - due to be completed before the end
of 1993 - should allow both its 'highway' transportation interests and the
aviation units to 'focus more sharply' on their respective markets.
Ryder shares gained Dollars  3/8 to Dollars 31 3/8 yesterday.
</TEXT>
