<PROFILE>_AN-DGACVAECFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>930701
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  01 JUL 93 / GEC advances 4% on lower sales
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALAN CANE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
STRONG growth in orders for turbines and trains coupled with careful cost
control helped GEC, the UK industrial group, push pre-tax profits to Pounds
863m last year, 4.1 per cent up on 1992.
Lord Weinstock, GEC managing director, expressed pessimism about the
immediate and medium-term prospects for the UK economy. 'Nothing much is
going to happen. Even when the recession ends, it will never get back to
where it was. Politicians are doing their best to damage confidence in
investment.'
Trading conditions both in the UK and overseas, where the company had 67 per
cent of sales, were poor. Turnover fell to Pounds 9.41bn from Pounds 9.43bn,
while operating profits slipped to Pounds 702m, against Pounds 695m, in the
year to March. Earnings per share rose nearly 6 per cent to 19.7p.
An increased final dividend of 7.62p will be paid, taking the total to
10.3p, up 7.3 per cent.
The company's efforts to contain costs and improve efficiency incurred
Pounds 90m in redundancy and restructuring charges, Pounds 25m more than the
year before. About 9,600 jobs were shed during the year, reducing staff
costs by 7 per cent and leaving the head count at 138,000.
The results were broadly in line with analysts' expectations. With the
market judging the performance to be sound but unexciting, the share price
gained 1p to close at 339p.
Lord Prior, GEC chairman, said the company was investing heavily in the Far
East and south east Asia, winning big contracts for power generation plant
and other equipment in China, Malaysia, Hong Kong and Indonesia.
The UK government was showing more willingness to back its exporters through
export credits in the style to which the UK's principal competitors were
accustomed. 'This change is to be welcomed, although Britain's manufacturing
base is now unfortunately too small to bring about a rapid reversal of our
large adverse balance of payments. To do this, consistent and supportive
policies are required over a period of years,' he said.
The company closed the year with net cash of Pounds 1.2bn, a Pounds 415m
increase. In addition, the group's share of net cash in joint ventures and
main associated companies was Pounds 985m, giving total cash of Pounds
2.18bn. Interest income was Pounds 149m, up 42 per cent despite lower rates.
The year-end order book stood at Pounds 12.3bn, 16 per cent higher than
1992.
