<HEADLINE>
FT  01 JUL 93 / Fiat admits it paid Pounds 19m bribes
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT GRAHAM
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   TURIN
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
MR GIOVANNI Agnelli, the chairman of Fiat, yesterday admitted that Italy's
largest private group had paid L50bn (Pounds 19m) in bribes to politicians
and their intermediaries over the past 10 years.
Mr Agnelli also disclosed that Fiat planned to raise up to L3,000bn this
year in asset sales to offset rising debt and the prospect of a 1993
operating loss close to L1,000bn.
Details of the bribes are in the as yet unpublished accounts, but Mr Agnelli
assured shareholders at the five-hour annual meeting: 'The total amount paid
out in (illicit) contributions to political parties over a decade by the
managers of Fiat group companies have had no significant repercussions on
the profits of the group.'
He said there was no case of accounts having been falsified because the
amounts were minimal in relation to assets, although some accounting
adjustments had been made.
He insisted that 'at consolidated level, we feel that the amount of these
payments in no way affects reliability of our financial statements since the
total is no more than 0.024 per cent of consolidated stockholders' equity'.
In this respect, Mr Agnelli yesterday showed his full faith in Mr Francesco
Paolo Mattioli, the chief financial officer and one of the two most senior
executives to be jailed while being interrogated on charges of alleged
corruption.
Defending the behaviour of some 20 executives in six companies involved in
magistrates' inquiries into corruption, Mr Agnelli said: 'Our managers claim
they were obliged to make such payments to prevent their companies from
being forced out of the market or to avoid harassment in the course of the
public works or supply contracts'.
Mr Agnelli was vague about the extent of his suspicions of the level of
corruption in Italy, but conceded he had had some reservations about
Cogefar-Impresit, the group's construction arm.
Mr Caesare Romiti, Fiat's chief executive officer, also defended his role in
the corruption affair.
He said that when the scale of Fiat's involvement became clear, a meeting of
the group's co-ordination committee was called and a new ethical code drawn
up.
Background, Page 28
