<HEADLINE>
FT  01 JUL 93 / US court ruling puts back Nafta approval
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NANCY DUNNE
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WASHINGTON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
APPROVAL of the North American Free Trade Agreement appears unlikely this
year after a US federal judge blocked its consideration by Congress when he
ruled that the treaty's impact on the environment had not been assessed.
Mr Mickey Kantor, the US trade representative, said the court's decision was
not in the public interest and the administration would request an expedited
appeal to a higher court. Meanwhile, it would continue to negotiate side
agreements governing labour and the environment with Canada and Mexico, the
other countries in the pact.
The pact is bogged down in those negotiations and faces a battle in a
Congress worried about lost jobs.
Although the higher court might come to a decision within two months, there
is no guarantee it would find in the administration's favour.
Judge Charles Richey found that Mrs Carla Hills, the former trade
representative, and ex-President George Bush had violated the Administrative
Procedures Act by negotiating and signing Nafta - due to be implemented in
January - without assessing its impact on the environment.
The judge said they had violated the National Environmental Policy Act
(NEPA), which requires an environmental impact statement for 'every
recommendation or report on proposals for legislation and other major
federal action significantly affecting the quality of the human
environment'.
Mr Kantor said that, besides interfering with the president's ability to
negotiate international agreements, the ruling raised serious doubts about
the Uruguay Round of trade talks, which might also require environmental
impact statements that could take months or years to compile.
If there is a delay in passing Nafta, Mexico's economy would suffer worst.
After the judge's decision, Mexico's stock market closed nearly 2 per cent
down. Investors had expected an early Nafta accord to boost growth.
The suit was brought by three environmental groups - Public Citizen, the
Sierra Club and Friends of the Earth. Mr Michael McCloskey, chairman of the
Sierra Club, said: 'This critical decision means trade agreements can never
be negotiated again without a conscious consideration of the environment.'
</TEXT>
