<HEADLINE>
FT  01 JUL 93 / News At Ten to stay put after wave of political protest
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RAYMOND SNODDY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
NEWS AT TEN, ITV's flagship television news programme, is to keep its
traditional slot for the foreseeable future after political protests at
suggestions that it might move to an earlier time.
The ITV companies that were suggesting the programme should be moved,
possibly to as early as 6.30pm, backed down yesterday in the face of firm
opposition from the Independent Television Commission and growing
parliamentary pressure which included a letter from Mr John Major, the prime
minister, expressing concern.
Sir George Russell, chairman of the ITC, wrote to the chairmen of all 15
regional ITV companies, warning them that they risked being in breach of
their broadcasting licences if they moved the main evening news without ITC
permission.
Eight of the companies had proposed in their bids for franchises running the
main evening news at 10pm, and the ITC legal advice is that those
commitments represent core obligations of their broadcasting licences.
Earlier, Mr Peter Brooke, the national heritage secretary, had suggested
that hostile parliamentary opinion on the News At Ten issue might have
flowed over to ITV ownership issues.
A number of large ITV companies want a relaxation of the rules to allow the
nine largest companies to take over each other. Such a move, if the
government goes ahead with it, would require a resolution in both houses of
parliament.
Although the ITV companies could challenge the ITC interpretation of its
powers in the courts, that is now unlikely to happen.
Mr Greg Dyke, chairman of the ITV council, last night said ITV would take
into consideration 'the full range of programming, public-interest,
commercial and legal issues, and it will only consider changes which are
permissible within the law'.
Mr Dyke said the issue was now unlikely to be resolved as planned at a
meeting on Monday.
ITV executives conceded last night that the idea of moving ITN to the early
evening had been an 'own goal', and a detailed business assessment had never
been prepared.
LWT staff petition, Page 7
