<HEADLINE>
FT  01 JUL 93 / Leading Article: Mates and worse
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
MR MICHAEL MATES, the former Northern Ireland minister, is convinced that
something is wrong with the system whereby the controversial businessman Mr
Asil Nadir is, or is not, being brought to justice. Who could disagree? Mr
Nadir has inflicted losses on hundreds of innocent people. He has obstructed
the administrators of Polly Peck in their attempts to retrieve something
from the wreckage. He has jumped bail, despite retaining enough money to
hire the best lawyers in the land.
Yet Mr Mates worries about the plight of Mr Nadir, now sunning himself in
northern Cyprus. He accuses the Serious Fraud Office (SFO) of a campaign to
undermine Mr Nadir's defence. In his own campaign, however, Mr Mates has
failed to deliver persuasive evidence of any conspiracy. There is a debate
to be had about the SFO's powers and its style, but Mr Mates has not made
the case for basing that case on the Nadir affair. Sir Nicholas Lyell, the
attorney-general, was right yesterday to reject an independent inquiry and
his decision to publish the relevant correspondence, albeit in edited form,
is welcome.
Mr Mates's priorities look quixotic. Mr Nadir, in contrast, is no Quixote,
but he must be congratulating himself on finding a Sancho Panza prepared to
defend his interests to the death. The government's priority should still be
to put Mr Nadir on trial. That may be a pious hope, but ministers have
little alternative but to apply further pressure on the Turkish authorities
to secure the return of a man who has made a fool of Britain's politicians
and its courts.
</TEXT>
